<dl id="n34033a"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n34" href="#n34033a">N34 (VI.B.27)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n34all.htm#n34033a"> 33(a)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> <sup>n</sup>P<sub>r</sub> <span class="strike"><span class="striketext">&#8735;</span></span> N! <sup>n</sup>P<sub>m</sub> <small>Not cancelled</small></blockquote> <dd class="well"> <ul class="list-inline" id="n34033a"><li>FW 285.15 </li><li><a href="../../flex/lg/lexlg.htm#n34033a">2010</a> </li><li><a href="../../flex/lg/l39lg.htm#n34033a">1939</a> </li><li><ms href="#n34033a">MS BL 47478-45</ms> </li><li>JJA 53:123 <a name="lgd8" href="../../FF/fdra/lda.htm#lgd8">Usage</a> </li><li> <a href="../../flex/lg/lgd8.htm#n34033a">Draft: II.2&sect;8.8</a></li> </ul> <blockquote class="sources"><font color="green">[The]</font> number of permutations of n things taken r at a time is (n-l)(n-2)&hellip;&hellip;(n-r+l). <i>Corr</i>. The number of permutations of n things taken all at a time is (n-1)(n-2)...... to n factors, or n(n-l)(n-2)......3.2.1. It is usual to denote this product by the symbol &#8735;n <font color="green">[=n!]</font>, which is read "factorial n". <br>We shall in future denote the number of permutations of n things taken r at a time by the symbol <sup>n</sup>P<sub>r</sub> so that <sup>n</sup>P<sub>r</sub> = n(n-l)(n-2)......(n-r+1); also <sup>n</sup>P<sub>n</sub> = &#8735;n. <small> Hall &amp; Knight, <a name="HSHK" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#HSHK"><cite title="source">Elementary Algebra for Schools</cite></a> (n.d) 321</small></blockquote> <mm class="note">Note: <i>Permutations</i> take account of the <i>order</i>, so that <i>abcd</i> is not the same as <i>acbd</i>. </mm> </dd></dl>
